Implement an AnchorSet type that holds multiple anchor directories (each
opened as a file descriptor at startup from trusted configuration), and
refactor all filesystem access paths to resolve a candidate path against
the full set rather than a single workspace root.

## Motivation

Currently SecureWorkspace (src/ava/tools/secure_workspace.{h,cpp}) supports
only a single anchor: workspace_dir. ToolContext (src/ava/tools/file_tools.h)
carries one std::shared_ptr<SecureWorkspace> and one workspace_dir path.
ToolDispatcher::create_strict (src/ava/agent/tool_dispatcher.cpp:1031)
opens that single workspace at startup. The permission check
is_within_workspace (src/ava/permissions/permission.cpp:212) uses
std::filesystem::weakly_canonical, which resolves symlinks on the
filesystem — exactly what we are trying to avoid.

The agent needs to write to multiple directories: the project workspace,
the spill_dir (session_path/spill), session storage, and potentially
user-configured additional writable directories. Each should be its own
anchor with independent symlink containment.

## Design

AnchorSet should hold a collection of anchor descriptors. Each anchor is:
  - An fd opened once at startup via plain openat against a trusted config
    path (same pattern as open_secure_root in context_loader.cpp:91 and
    SecureWorkspace::open in secure_workspace.cpp).
  - A lexical root path for path-matching purposes.

A candidate path is resolved by:
  1. Lexically normalizing the candidate (no filesystem canonicalization).
  2. Finding the anchor whose root is a lexical prefix of the candidate.
  3. Using open_beneath on that anchor's fd for the relative portion.

If no anchor matches, the path is rejected. If multiple anchors match, the
most specific (longest) prefix wins. Symlinks are followed per-anchor:
a symlink in anchor A pointing into anchor B is rejected (it escapes A's
boundary), even though B is also in the set.

## What needs to change

- New AnchorSet type (likely in src/ava/tools/ or src/ava/core/) replacing
  the single-SecureWorkspace model. May wrap multiple SecureWorkspace
  instances or refactor SecureWorkspace to hold multiple fds.
- ToolContext (file_tools.h:102-155): replace workspace_dir +
  shared_ptr<SecureWorkspace> with shared_ptr<AnchorSet>.
- ToolDispatcher::create_strict (tool_dispatcher.cpp:1031): open all
  configured anchors at startup, populate AnchorSet.
- is_within_workspace (permission.cpp:212): replace weakly_canonical with
  lexical comparison against the AnchorSet.
- file_io.cpp write_file_unlocked (line 522): route writes through
  AnchorSet instead of single secure_workspace.
- agent_loop.cpp (line 830): wire AnchorSet into ToolContext.
- Config: add a way to specify additional writable directories at startup
  (e.g., in OpenOptions or a new config field).

## Constraints

- open_beneath (src/ava/core/open_beneath.{h,cpp}) is the central primitive
  for all post-startup path resolution. It uses openat2 RESOLVE_BENEATH on
  Linux 5.6+ (follows non-escaping symlinks, rejects escaping ones with
  EXDEV) and falls back to an O_NOFOLLOW component walk (rejects ALL
  symlinks) on older systems.
- Anchor fds are opened with plain openat at startup from trusted config
  paths. open_beneath is only for untrusted relative paths on top of an
  anchor. openat2 RESOLVE_BENEATH rejects absolute symlinks unconditionally
  (EXDEV), so anchors themselves must be opened directly (see
  context_loader.cpp:91 comment and SecureWorkspace::open).
- No weakly_canonical or lexically_canonical for untrusted paths. Only
  lexical normalization (lexically_normal) is permitted.
- renameat/unlinkat on final component is safe only when target_name is a
  single component (ASSERTed in StagedWrite constructor via
  target_name_.filename() == target_name_).
- All path/name members in StagedWrite and stage_write use
  std::filesystem::path, not std::string.

## Already done (prerequisite goal 01-unify-open_beneath)

- open_beneath extracted to ava::core::open_beneath with mode_t parameter.
- SecureWorkspace::resolve(AllowMissing) uses open_beneath prefix walk
  (follows non-escaping symlinks, rejects escaping).
- SecureWorkspace::stage_write uses open_beneath for parent walk, temp
  file creation, and final-component symlink escape probe.
- All raw openat calls with AI-influenced paths replaced with open_beneath.
- lexical_workspace_path does lexical-only validation (no canonicalization).
- StagedWrite members use std::filesystem::path.
- Tests: test_secure_workspace_symlink_containment (8 tests covering
  read/write/resolve through non-escaping and escaping symlinks),
  test_secure_workspace_symlinked_root.
- All 79 tests pass.

## Verification

- All existing 79 tests must continue to pass.
- New tests for multi-anchor scenarios:
  - Write to anchor A succeeds; write to anchor B succeeds.
  - Path outside all anchors is rejected.
  - Symlink in anchor A pointing into anchor B is rejected (cross-anchor
    escape).
  - Symlink within anchor A pointing within anchor A is accepted.
  - is_within_workspace uses lexical comparison, not weakly_canonical.
- aap-build and aap-test must pass.
- git diff --check must be clean.
